content:
I'll admit - I had to crunch the numbers several times to see why this movie only rated a 6 on my scale. IMDB composite rating is currently at 8.3. Everyone remembers 'Heat' as a 'great' film. The truth is, when watching it 28 years later, it's only a 'good' film.In 1995, film making was still being influenced by epics like 'Scarface' (1983). Today, 'Scarface' seems a little long, and we could all do without so many 1980's music interlude scenes. So, for '1990's Film', this is a great crime drama. The cinematography was top-notch. The casting was amazing on all levels. But, this was not among the best performances of Pacino, or DeNiro, or Kilmer. It was a long movie with a great cast and a great shoot-out scene. Every cliche ever written into a crime drama is in this film, and all of them are over-dramatised.So, if you have 3 hours, take the good with the bad and watch 'Heat' next time you need a crime drama for ' '90's Movie Night'.RealReview Posting Scoring Criteria:
Acting: 1/1;
Casting: 1/1;
Directing: 1/1;
Story: 1/1;
Writing/Screenplay: 0.5/1;
Total Base Score = 4.5Modifiers (+ or -):Cinematography: +1 (The shoot-out scene outside of the bank is one of the best in film history.);Ensemble Cast: +1 (Not only were the main roles cast well (and, there were about 10 of them), but the bit parts were also awarded to up-and-coming actors that would have great careers - such as Jeremy Piven and Hank Azaria.);Editing-Too Long: -0.5 (If we were to cut about 25 minutes of superfluous dialog and B-role footage of L. A., this would be a better film.);Total RealReview Rating: 6.

I love the Hollywood 70's new wave. And I absolutely love The Godfather... however the Al Pacino bits in Godfather II were not my favourite (they would be the De Niro bits)... and an Al Pacino festival curated by me would be very short. Scarface for the chuckles, and Carlitos Way is a favourite... however for such a mentioned actor I'm not on team Pacino..So I need to write 600 character... here I go;
Scarecrow (1973) is good.Serpico (1973) is well regarded but not a favourite of mine. It's not bad; just not on my playlist,
Dog Day Afternoon (1975). Another New Hollywood title that I can't connect with. It's frequently referred to as a classic..I could ho on, however..,.
